{"key":"processedPost-12498189","value":{"id":12498189,"first":12491300,"last":12499553,"when":1272903518,"utime":"05/03/10 07:18 PM","content":"Listen guys.&nbsp; The micropore tape over the holes works to prevent contamination from entering the jars/verm filter <b>before</b> you inoculate.&nbsp; Otherwise, contaminant spores can be on top of the verm, and your needle can push them through to the inside.&nbsp; That's the only reason to use it.&nbsp; It's not needed but is an added insurance policy.<br /><br />After inoculation, you can leave the wound in the tape exposed.<br /><br />A verm filter will work unless you jerk with your jars too much and disturb it.&nbsp; The vermiculite filter must be left alone to work.&nbsp; If you turn the jars upside down back and forth a few times, you stir those contaminant spores down into your substrate.<br />RR","title":"Re: To Breathe or Not To Breathe? That is my question?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}